To add user identity information in the web chat integration, you can set the value of the `user_id` property. If you do not pass an identifier for the user when the session begins, the web chat creates one for you in the form of a first-party cookie with a generated anonymous ID. This cookie remains active for 45 days. For more information, see [Adding user identity information](https://cloud.ibm.com/docs/assistant-data?topic=assistant-data-deploy-web-chatdeploy-web-chat-userid).

If you don't want to use the built-in user identity handling, you can also generate a randomized universally unique ID to represent each anonymous user. For more information about UUIDs, see [RFC 4122](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc4122.html).

It is important to choose a non-human-identifiable ID that doesn't change throughout the customer lifecycle. For example, don't use a person's email address as the user ID. In fact, the user\_id syntax must meet the requirements for header fields as defined in [RFC 7230](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7230section-3.2).

Here's an example of how to set the `user_id` property:

<script>
window.watsonAssistantChatOptions = {
integrationID: 'YOUR_INTEGRATION_ID',
region: 'YOUR_REGION',
serviceInstanceID: 'YOUR_SERVICE_INSTANCE',
user_id: 'YOUR_USER_ID',
onLoad: function(instance) {
instance.render();
}
};
setTimeout(function(){
const t=document.createElement('script');
t.src = "https://web-chat.global.assistant.watson.cloud.ibm.com/loading.js";
document.head.appendChild(t);
}, 1500);
</script>

Just replace `'YOUR_USER_ID'` with the desired user ID.

